<!-- DAY 2 -->
<div class="section" id="day2">
  <h2><span class="day-label">Day 2 &mdash; Saturday 10 October</span>&ldquo;Freud&rsquo;s Vienna&rdquo;</h2>

  <div class="photo-grid" style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr);gap:6px;margin:15px 0;border-radius:10px;overflow:hidden;">
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Caf&eacute; Landtmann" style="width:100%;height:200px;object-fit:cover;display:block;">
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Vienna State Opera" style="width:100%;height:200px;object-fit:cover;display:block;">
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Vienna old town" style="width:100%;height:200px;object-fit:cover;display:block;">
  </div>

  <div class="freud-box">
    <p><strong>The Freud thread through today:</strong> Brunch at his favourite caf&eacute; &rarr; his home and practice for 47 years &rarr; a walk through his neighbourhood &rarr; Europe&rsquo;s first asylum &rarr; the grand caf&eacute; where he met patients &rarr; the Opera. By the end of the day, we&rsquo;ll know this city through his eyes.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">11:00</div><div class="timeline-desc"><strong>Caf&eacute; Landtmann</strong> for brunch &mdash; Freud&rsquo;s actual favourite caf&eacute;. Red leather booths, velvet upholstery, plush drapes. Opposite the Burgtheater on the Ringstra&szlig;e. One of the best &ldquo;this is Vienna&rdquo; moments on the trip.</div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">12:30</div><div class="timeline-desc">Walk 8 mins north to the <strong>Sigmund Freud Museum</strong>, Berggasse 19 &mdash; his home and practice for 47 years (1891&ndash;1938). The famous couch isn&rsquo;t here (it went to London when he fled) but an AR installation brings it back. Original belongings, family films, personal letters, first editions. The museum caf&eacute; does a &ldquo;Sigmund Freud&rdquo; champagne. The shop sells a &ldquo;repression&rdquo; eraser and a Freud bath duck. Allow 1&ndash;1.5 hours. <em>Entry: &euro;15 adults. Open daily except Tues, 10am&ndash;6pm.</em></div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">14:00</div><div class="timeline-desc">Walk through the <strong>Alsergrund</strong> (the 9th district &mdash; Freud&rsquo;s neighbourhood). Past the <strong>University of Vienna</strong> where he taught, through <strong>Sigmund Freud Park</strong>. This is where the day really comes alive.</div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">14:30</div><div class="timeline-desc"><strong>Narrenturm</strong> (&ldquo;Fools&rsquo; Tower&rdquo;) &mdash; Europe&rsquo;s first purpose-built asylum for the mentally ill (1784), now a pathological anatomy museum. The old cells house the collection. Fascinating, eerie, and very Freud-adjacent. No photography allowed. Allow 1 hour. <em>Entry: &euro;8. Open Wed&ndash;Sat only, 10am&ndash;5pm.</em></div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">16:30</div><div class="timeline-desc"><strong>Caf&eacute; Central</strong> &mdash; the grandest of them all. Vaulted ceilings, piano music, marble columns. Freud reportedly met patients here. Trotsky and Lenin played chess here. Also associated with the city&rsquo;s intellectual and political salon culture. Sachertorte and a Melange. Linger.</div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">18:00</div><div class="timeline-desc">Back to apartment. Change for the evening.</div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">20:00</div><div class="timeline-desc"><strong>Vienna State Opera</strong> &mdash; a 10-minute walk from our apartment. Check what&rsquo;s on for 10 October and book seats in advance, or try for standing tickets from &euro;4 on the day.</div></div>
    <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-time">22:30</div><div class="timeline-desc">Optional drinks near the Ringstra&szlig;e. Only if we still have the energy.</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box">
    <p><strong>&#9749; Caf&eacute; Landtmann</strong> &mdash; <em>The Freud connection:</em> Founded 1873, this was Freud&rsquo;s regular morning caf&eacute;. He is said to have taken his coffee here daily, reading the papers in the red leather booths. Gustav Mahler, Marlene Dietrich, and more recently Hillary Clinton and Paul McCartney have all sat at the same tables. Located directly opposite the Burgtheater and a short walk from the university where Freud taught.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box">
    <p><strong>&#9749; Caf&eacute; Central</strong> &mdash; <em>The Freud connection:</em> Freud is reported to have met patients here over coffee before taking them back to Berggasse 19 for sessions. But Central&rsquo;s significance runs wider &mdash; its regulars included Trotsky, Lenin, Stefan Zweig, Arthur Schnitzler, and Alfred Adler. It was the intellectual nerve centre of early 20th-century Vienna. The vaulted ceilings and marble columns are as grand now as they were then.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box">
    <p><strong>&#9888; Narrenturm:</strong> Open Wednesday to Saturday only, 10am&ndash;5pm. We&rsquo;re going on a Saturday &mdash; fine.</p>
    <p><strong>&#9888; Freud Museum:</strong> Open daily except Tuesdays, 10am&ndash;6pm. Also fine for Saturday.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box">
    <p><strong>&#128694; Day 2 walking route:</strong> Caf&eacute; Landtmann &rarr; Freud Museum &rarr; Narrenturm &rarr; Caf&eacute; Central &rarr; Opera. Total: ~4 km, north to south.</p>
    <p><a href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Caf%C3%A9+Landtmann,+Universit%C3%A4tsring+4,+1010+Wien/Sigmund+Freud+Museum,+Berggasse+19,+1090+Wien/Narrenturm,+Spitalgasse+2,+1090+Wien/Caf%C3%A9+Central,+Herrengasse+14,+1010+Wien/Vienna+State+Opera,+Opernring+2,+1010+Wien/@48.2109,16.3628,14z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m32!4m31!1m5!1m1!1s0x476d079c73d0e89b:0xb267c9cd76317032!2m2!1d16.3615!2d48.2115!1m5!1m1!1s0x476d07bbd806e0e5:0x5fa5f935f7f0ca57!2m2!1d16.3631!2d48.2186!1m5!1m1!1s0x476d07c0a85ea2b3:0x53454523b78887039!2m2!1d16.3534!2d48.2185!1m5!1m1!1s0x476d0797f73630af:0x5b76fb473f424e49!2m2!1d16.3654!2d48.2104!1m5!1m1!1s0x476d079c861df5d7:0xfd5926258d377e56!2m2!1d16.3692!2d48.2034!3e2" target="_blank" style="color:#c4a97d;">&#128205; Open walking route in Google Maps</a></p>
  </div>
